Raft Consensus Deep Dive - School Election Style

The Analogy
Think of Raft like a school election for class president. The president maintains the official class notebook which is your distributed database.

Raft Role	        School Role	                    What They Do
Leader	            Class President	                Maintains official notebook, makes decisions
Followers	        Regular Students	            Follow president's rules, keep copies
Candidate	        Student Running for President	Temporary during elections

How Elections Work - Leader Election

When there is no president or current president fails:

Timeout Period: Each student waits a random time
Becoming Candidate: First student to get bored becomes candidate and asks for votes
Voting: Other students vote once per term. Need majority to win

New Leader: Winner becomes president until next election
Real benefit: Automatic failover. If leader dies, cluster elects a new leader in under 1 second.

How Data is Saved Log Replication
The class notebook has three rules:

Rule	            What Happens
Before Writing	    President logs change in personal diary first
Replication	        President makes classmates copy the note
Commitment	        Only notes copied by majority become official

Real benefit: No data loss. Even if leader crashes, the log survives.

Key Concepts
Distributed Consensus
Problem: How do multiple computers agree on data when some may fail?
Solution: Raft ensures all nodes eventually have same data if majority are alive.

Log Persistence
Every change is recorded in order as an append-only log.

Example log:

Term 1: Add user Alice
Term 1: Delete user Bob
Term 2: Update config timeout to 30 seconds

Key-Value Store
Like a dictionary where Key is a unique identifier and Value is the associated data.

Example: Key = /students/ali, Value = {"grade": "A", "age": 10}

Complete Raft Flow
Step	Action
1	    Client sends request like kubectl create pod
2	    Only leader handles write requests
3	    Leader adds to its log as uncommitted
4	    Followers copy the log entry
5	    When majority acknowledge, leader commits
6	    Leader tells client success

etcd Specifics - Kubernetes Brain
Setting	Value

Default cluster size	3 or 5 nodes
Quorum for 3 nodes	Need 2 for majority
Quorum for 5 nodes	Need 3 for majority

Data directory	/var/lib/etcd/ with snap and wal folders

Common Failure Scenarios

Failure	            What Happens
Network Partition	Minority side cannot elect leader. Majority side continues normally
Leader Crash	    New election in under 1 second. No data loss because of WAL
Follower Lag	    Follower automatically catches up from leader

Quick Summary
Term	        Simple Meaning
Leader	        Handles all writes
Followers	    Copy data from leader
Quorum	        Majority of nodes needed
WAL	            Log before write for recovery
Commitment	    Data is safe when majority have it

Real Benefit for IT Working
Raft gives you strong consistency without complex configuration. Your Kubernetes cluster continues working even if 2 out of 5 etcd nodes fail. No manual intervention needed. Automatic leader election and log replication handle everything.

